{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Arbitrary `tokenOut` lets withdrawers steal unrelated tokens held by the zap","locations":["0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:427-431","0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:465-497","0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:572-573"],"claim":"`withdraw()` only uses `tokenOut` to decide whether to consolidate into `token1`; otherwise it consolidates into `token0`, but it still transfers `IERC20(tokenOut)` at the end without validating that the contract actually holds the withdrawn proceeds in that asset. A caller can therefore request any ERC20 currently held by the zap instead of the asset produced by the withdrawal.","impact":"Any user with a withdrawable LP position can drain unrelated balances from the contract. Because nonzero `basketId` deposits keep LP tokens in the zap and only update internal bookkeeping, an attacker can withdraw a small position while setting `tokenOut` to the pair LP token and steal other users' basket-backed LP. The real withdrawal proceeds remain stranded in the contract, leaving basket accounting undercollateralized.","paths":["Basket users deposit with `basketId != 0`, so LP tokens stay in the zap balance and only `balanceOf[account][pair][basketId]` is incremented.","An attacker obtains a small withdrawable position for the same pair.","The attacker calls `withdraw(attacker, token0, token1, amount, pair, basketId, address(0), emptyPath, ...)`.","`withdraw()` removes liquidity and recombines into `token0`/`token1`, but the final transfer sends `IERC20(pair)` from the contract's shared balance to the attacker."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Missing authorization on `account` lets arbitrary callers consume users' token and LP approvals","locations":["0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:397-410","0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:442-447"],"claim":"`deposit()` and the `basketId == 0` branch of `withdraw()` pull funds from an arbitrary `account` with `safeTransferFrom`, but neither function requires `msg.sender == account` nor any signature-based authorization from that account.","impact":"Anyone can spend tokens or LP tokens from any victim that has approved the zap. Although outputs are returned to the victim account, the attacker controls the target pair, swap routes, basket selection, and minimum amounts, so they can forcibly rebalance or unwind the victim at attacker-chosen times and prices and externalize the loss through MEV or market manipulation.","paths":["A victim grants the zap an allowance for an ERC20 input token or LP token.","An attacker calls `deposit(victim, ...)` or `withdraw(victim, ..., basketId = 0, ...)` using attacker-chosen pair parameters and routes.","The zap pulls the victim's approved assets and executes the forced swap/liquidity flow without verifying the caller is authorized by the victim."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Deposit half-swap is fully sandwichable because it uses `amountOutMin = 0`","locations":["0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:423-425","0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:528-535"],"claim":"`_depositSwap()` computes the optimal half-swap from current reserves, then executes `swapExactTokensForTokens(swapAmount, 0, ...)` with no slippage floor. The later `addLiquidity()` minimums do not protect this intermediate swap.","impact":"Deposits into thin or manipulable pools can be sandwiched so the zap performs its most price-sensitive leg at an attacker-controlled rate, causing the depositor to lose a large fraction of value before liquidity is added.","paths":["A user submits a deposit into a target pair.","An attacker front-runs to move the pair price against the zap's calculated half-swap.","`_depositSwap()` executes with `amountOutMin = 0` and accepts the manipulated output.","The attacker back-runs to restore price and captures the depositor's loss."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Operators can directly drain all basket and residual assets via `withdrawToken`","locations":["0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:427-431","0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:572-583","0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:602-609"],"claim":"The contract custodies LP tokens for nonzero basket IDs in its own balance, but any address marked as an `operator` can call `withdrawToken()` to transfer arbitrary ERC20s or ETH out of the contract with no linkage to basket accounting or user balances.","impact":"A malicious or compromised operator can instantly steal all LP tokens backing basket positions, along with any stranded swap outputs or ETH held by the zap. This is a direct loss-of-funds backdoor over all custodial balances stored in the contract.","paths":["Users deposit with `basketId != 0`, which leaves LP tokens in the zap while only internal balances are updated.","`operatorSetter` designates an address as an operator.","The operator calls `withdrawToken(pair, operator, IERC20(pair).balanceOf(address(this)))` or drains other ERC20/ETH balances.","Users' basket balances remain recorded, but the backing assets are gone."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Native-ETH withdrawals are broken for non-WETH pairs","locations":["0x364f17a23ae4350319b7491224d10df5796190bc/contracts/LiquidXv2Zap.sol:465-500"],"claim":"When `tokenOut == address(0)`, `withdraw()` uses `wrappedETH` only for branch selection, but unless one leg of the pair is already WETH it never swaps the withdrawn assets into WETH before calling `IWETH(wrappedETH).withdraw(vamount[2])`. The alternative `wpath` route is also broken in this case because it tries to approve and swap `tokenOut` at the zero address.","impact":"Users cannot exit most non-WETH pairs into native ETH through the zap. These withdrawals revert after liquidity removal and intermediate swaps, breaking a core withdrawal path and forcing users to withdraw only as ERC20 assets instead of ETH.","paths":["A user calls `withdraw(..., tokenOut = address(0), wpath = empty)` for a pair that does not include WETH.","The function consolidates into `token0` or `token1`, not WETH.","It then calls `IWETH(wrappedETH).withdraw(vamount[2])` without holding WETH, so the transaction reverts.","If the user supplies a non-empty `wpath`, the function instead tries to approve `tokenOut` at `address(0)`, which also breaks the ETH conversion path."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing Validation for Identical Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`deposit()` and `withdraw()` require `factory.getPair(token0, token1) != address(0)`, so identical-token inputs are rejected unless the factory itself exposes such a pair."},{"title":"Potential Integer Overflow in `_calculateSwapAmount`","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Solidity 0.8 reverts on arithmetic overflow, and realistic reserve/input sizes are far below the range needed to make this a practical protocol issue."},{"title":"Operators Can Withdraw from Any User's Basket","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The nonzero-`basketId` branch only lets operators force a withdrawal back to the same `account`; it does not redirect funds. Any operator theft is already more directly covered by `withdrawToken`."},{"title":"No Deadline Check on Router Interactions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Passing `block.timestamp` as the router deadline forces same-block execution rather than allowing indefinite pending execution, so the stated issue is backwards."},{"title":"OperatorSetter Role is Irreversible","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance/trust-model concern, not a standalone exploitable vulnerability in the contract logic."},{"title":"Balance Check Before `transferFrom` Allows Token Manipulation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The before/after balance pattern is a standard way to support fee-on-transfer tokens here, and no concrete reentrant accounting exploit is supported by the contract state transitions."},{"title":"Refund Calculation Can Underflow","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`addLiquidity()` returns the amounts actually consumed, which are bounded by the desired amounts; the subtraction only reverts if the router breaks its interface guarantees."},{"title":"Unrestricted ETH Receive Function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Accepting unsolicited ETH may create recoverable dust, but by itself it does not create realistic protocol-level harm."},{"title":"Missing Return Value Check on Reward Claim","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`IRewarderv2.claim()` is declared with no return value, so there is no unchecked boolean or amount to validate."}]}
